1. Roll with the punches.

One thing‚Äôs certain in this life: you‚Äôre gonna get hit. So brace yourself, take the punch, and move on. Stop sweating the small stuff. All the bad things in your life happened for a reason. Use them for motivation. Let go of the past because what happened to you yesterday doesn‚Äôt affect who you are today. Accept that this is exactly where you‚Äôre supposed to be at this very moment and everything that has happened to you is part of your journey.

2. Be a student of life.

Want to improve yourself today? You‚Äôre already doing it. Learning something new and seeking knowledge and wisdom is a key part of constantly improving. Reset, Refocus, Readjust, Restart‚Ä¶As Many Times As You Need To!
.
.
How many times do you feel like you‚Äôve just lost your focus and you need a reset? This happens to me about mid-week, every week. If I‚Äôm lucky I can make it to Thursday before I feel like I‚Äôve gone way off course. 
I‚Äôm here to tell you it‚Äôs okay to have a mental reset moment. To look at your surroundings and say, ‚Äúhey this isn‚Äôt working!‚Äù Maybe something isn‚Äôt working right and you have to adjust things‚Ä¶once again. Or maybe it‚Äôs just your thinking that needs a kick in the rear end?

All I‚Äôm saying here is that it‚Äôs perfectly okay to reset, refocus, reschedule, or re-do something to make it better, to feel better, to live better, to enjoy life more. .
.
Redo it as many times as you need to. .
.
Go for a walk to clear your mind, then get back at it. You never know what some fresh air can do to a tired overworked mind. Sometimes that mental break or moment where you realize you just need to start over and reset yourself can truly lead to better things or the answers you were looking for.

Restarting, resetting your mind, or moving things around in your schedule is much better than giving up. Postponing something for more clarity and for your wellbeing does not mean you‚Äôve given up. And you can even say, heck I just don‚Äôt want to pursue that right now. You have to prioritize and remember you can‚Äôt do everything. 
Whatever your reset moment reveals, it should make you more productive, while also making you happier. .
.
.

What are toxins and how does cupping work to release the body of toxins?
.
.
üî∂Answerüî∂
Toxins are cell waste (like lactic acid, food preservatives, pesticides, hormones) that become stagnate in tissue because the circulatory system did not flush it out all the way.  When you get cupping done, it pulls (through suction) the stagnation out of the tissues and brings it to skin level. The pores then expand and discharge the waste and toxins. The rest of the toxins not brought to the surface will be properly flushed out in the circulatory and lymphatic system. In the picture attached, you can see how the toxins released vary in color and appearance based specifically on what the body has been holding in the tissues.
.
.
It has been found that cupping can affect tissues up to 4 inches deep; affecting blood vessels, fascia, muscles, and scar tissue. ... It is used specifically to decompress adhesions and scar tissue, relax muscles in spasm, decrease trigger point pain, and decrease tissue changes and inflammation following trauma.
üî∂Please noteüî∂
The cupping marks shown do not hurt. The marks again are a result of the toxins your body was holding.

I truly hope that this helps with any concerns
